caption: Charming shops along a quiet street.  Prices were higher than some further out neighborhoods as expected. Interesting and authentic collections of small antiques, modern crafts, design ideas, galleries, and more.

This was disappointing. The area did not match the hype about being there.  There was much more going on just a couple of hundred feet away at Rue Saint Antoine. There is lots more food to choose from and a much more lively street.
Little shopping complex in the area of Saint Paul near Rue de Charlemagne. Unfortunately many shops are closed only 1 restaurant/ coffee shop open.

Nice and quiet corner in the very centre of Paris, two minutes walking from Rue de Rivoli and the Seine. Not expect anything fancy, but it is definitely a place where to find a relaxed and calm environment. Also shops and bars/restos inside are fine. Good on a city walk
One of our favourite areas in Paris.... lots of food,  drinking & shopping options but away from the big dept stores
Tranquil, peaceful, and unique little shops in the center of the Marais. Beautiful area in which to be a flÃ¢neur, just wander around and soak up the atmosphere. Definitely a place to discover.
A haven of antique shops, art galleries and craft boutiques, the Village Saint-Paul is home to some 200 antique dealers selling everything from medieval pieces to 1960s pop memorabilia.
It is special. Kind of hidden place in Paris / Marais, with cafes, boutiques, interior courtyards... It is cute. Worth a stroll.

construction is on going and all shops are closed.. doesnt feel like it is worth a visit even after the construction is completed unless you are on a guided tour to understand more about history of the place
Pleasant to walk through, some bird houses in the trees. It was very quiet when I visited in December.
Cute and tranquil neighbourhood with Parisian history.

This is indeed a cute little place tucked out of the way.  Though when I strolled through, there were only two shops open, multiple vacant storefronts, and nothing that I would say warrants a specific trip to see this place.

There are a few shops but really not much.  Some eateries and a quiet space away from busier side of Paris. Shops are mainly bric a brac (but suggested as antiques but not really) or odd assortments of clothes. Most interesting but were the trees which had quite a few bird houses... almost bird villages, but just a square of them.
A nice little quiet place in the center of Paris with nice little cafes and shopd

A few interior courts linked to each other, *some* antique shops, many of them closed. Cyclo-tourists, homeless people. Nowhere near the enthusiastic description of a wonderful little place that I had been told. There's much more to see anywhere else.
Amazing place but didn't get to see it all as not everything was open due to armistice day. I would double check opening times though, as some places may open up later than you'd expect.
Incredible castle medieval in the middle of the city. The history is fantastic  and not very well know for regular tourist in Paris. Worth the visit and is very close to Place des Vosges.
Cute village , nice streets and local shops and cafes. Its close to Vosges square (Maison de Victor Hugo museum)

We came for the antiques shops. Most of what was there was not very high quality; and there were not many shops. The best of the shops were those selling antique glass. For antiques, you can do better in Carre des Antiquaires district or, a step lower in prices and quality, Le Village Suisse.
A BEAUTIFUL area with great vibes, shops and views.
Not a lot of thing were open. But its easy to find. Walk and take in some history The wall, the library or hotel, the church . Its a nice walk
I'm not into antiques, but this is a cool place with some nice shops and would be a beautiful quiet square on which to sit outside and have lunch.
There really wasnâ€™t anything there. Waste of time.  Nothing seemed to be open.  Thought I was in the wrong place.

Village Saint Paul is pittoresque as it can be, nothing reminds of baron Haussman's Paris here near the walls of once Bastille fortres.  Time seems to run at a small pace while you stroll around, sometimes to only get to where you started from, in and out antique or old lace shops.
Love the food and ambience ðŸ˜Š
A nice area in the middle of the city is worth seeing if you're on your way, but you don't need to go especially for it
A little boring, still a nice original place. Unfortunately it seems like thereâ€™s some engineering projects in this moment, so thereâ€™s not much things to watch.
Ok spot to walk around I suppose. Nothing special when compared to any average city side street though.
The place looks interesting and beautiful but there are some renovations going on right now.
Should be a very nice area but it's under construction at the moment, and seems the scheduled time to finish has been postponed
Interesting if you are into antiques but not as vibrant as some travel guides may suggest.
Wonderful....I sat and had a glass of wine watching time flow by.
Came on a Monday and couldn't tell if it was closed on Monday, being renovated, or simply defunct. Nothing was open and it was a mess.
Everything is in construction at the moment. Not worth the visit. Probably there's more activity in the evening in the bars and restaurants.
Don't miss the monthly flea market! You can find all sorts of treasures!  They post the schedule on their website.
Hidden area.. Very cozy and nice relaxed atmosphere... as if a small village is hidden within the big city of Paris
stepped into this beautiful area by complete surprise. Sunday market and small intimate cafes
A beautiful spot in the middle of Paris. A lot of small stores and a few coffee shops. Just come in and escape the city for a moment.
The Village St. Paul has a few crammed, tiny antique shops.  Lots of construction going on but not worth a trip at the moment!!
Unfortunately we walked all the way there to find 3 shops open. Still under construction. Not worthwhile at all.
Nice place to buy some antiques. Not open all the time.
Great area in LA Marais. We loved it
humongous disappointment: no charm, no life, nothing to really go there for.
Quaint, but nothing you don't see by doing lots of walking around Paris
Beautiful place. I live that is hidden.
Nothing much was open unfortunately.
Nice place
Good plan for a warm afternoon walk
